<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1509,2001]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1761,1785]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is widely distributed in the Indo-west Pacific. In the Persian Gulf and Gulf of 
<collectingCountry box="[1338,1409,1761,1785]" name="Oman" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Oman</collectingCountry>
, it is one of the common porcellanid crabs in the high intertidal zone with rocky and stony structure. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Audouin" baseAuthorityYear="1826" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boscii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Petrolisthes boscii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has sometimes taxonomically been confused with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Man" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[806,974,1833,1857]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moluccensis">
<emphasis box="[806,820,1834,1857]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[837,974,1833,1857]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">moluccensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Nobili, G." box="[1043,1196,1833,1857]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="13 - 159" refId="ref51383" refString="Nobili, G. (1906 a) Crustaces decapodes et stomatopodes. In: Mission J. Bonnier et Ch. Perez (Golfe Persique, 1901). Bulletin Scientifique de la France et de la Belgique, 40, 13 - 159, pls. 2 - 7." type="journal article" year="1906">Nobili 1906a</bibRefCitation>
), but as 
<bibRefCitation author="Haig, J." box="[1297,1436,1833,1857]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" pagination="49 - 65" refId="ref47698" refString="Haig, J. (1966) The Porcellanidae (Crustacea, Anomura) of the Iranian Gulf and Gulf of Oman. Videnskabelige Meddelelser fra Dansk Naturhistorisk Forening i Kobenhaven, 129, 49 - 65." type="journal article" year="1966">Haig (1966)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned, it is clearly different from the latter by having short setae on the inner side of the fingers, and by lacking spines on the anterior margin of walking legs. Adults differ from young specimens (CL &lt;
<quantity box="[1167,1233,1905,1929]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
) in two following characters: strata on carapace and appendages are prominently shorter and usually squamiform (Paul’son 1975: 93–94); the front of adults is clearly broader than long and triangular.
</paragraph>
